1
00:01:19,168 --> 00:01:20,918
<i>The voice you hear</i>

2
00:01:20,959 --> 00:01:23,334
<i>is not my speaking voice</i>

3
00:01:23,376 --> 00:01:25,376
<i>but my mind's voice.</i>

4
00:01:29,876 --> 00:01:32,626
<i>I have not spoken
since I was six years old.</i>

5
00:01:34,876 --> 00:01:36,459
<i>No-one knows why.</i>

6
00:01:36,459 --> 00:01:38,418
<i>Not even me.</i>

7
00:01:38,459 --> 00:01:40,418
Come on!

8
00:01:50,834 --> 00:01:53,584
<i>My father says
it is a dark talent,</i>

9
00:01:53,626 --> 00:01:55,793
<i>and the day I take it
into my head to stop breathing</i>

10
00:01:55,834 --> 00:01:57,293
<i>will be my last.</i>

11
00:02:04,793 --> 00:02:08,084
<i>Today he married me to a man
I've not yet met.</i>

12
00:02:09,626 --> 00:02:13,126
<i>Soon my daughter and I shall
join him in his own country.</i>

13
00:02:15,584 --> 00:02:18,959
<i>My husband said my muteness
does not bother him.</i>

14
00:02:19,001 --> 00:02:22,376
<i>He writes - and hark this -</i>

15
00:02:22,418 --> 00:02:25,043
<i>God loves dumb creatures,
so why not he?</i>

16
00:02:29,793 --> 00:02:32,168
<i>Were good
he had God's patience...</i>

17
00:02:34,876 --> 00:02:37,501
<i>..for silence affects everyone
in the end.</i>

18
00:02:41,168 --> 00:02:45,834
<i>The strange thing is
I don't think myself silent.</i>

19
00:02:45,876 --> 00:02:47,876
<i>That is because of my piano.</i>

20
00:02:49,793 --> 00:02:51,543
<i>I shall miss it on the journey.</i>

21
00:03:52,501 --> 00:03:55,251
Give me your hand.
Come on!

22
00:03:57,168 --> 00:03:58,959
You're with me!

23
00:04:00,251 --> 00:04:01,584
I've got the lady.

24
00:04:10,293 --> 00:04:12,543
Easy! It's Sunday.

25
00:04:55,376 --> 00:04:56,959
There you go.
Watch it!

26
00:04:56,959 --> 00:04:59,251
There you are, madam.
Paddington Station.

27
00:05:00,918 --> 00:05:02,459
Over here, me lovely.

28
00:05:06,918 --> 00:05:09,043
Alright, lads. Unbutton.

29
00:05:09,084 --> 00:05:12,001
I could piss like a toff.
Get that boat unloaded.

30
00:05:12,043 --> 00:05:13,876
Come on! First!

31
00:05:15,959 --> 00:05:18,584
The six whole months
I spent in Dublin...

32
00:05:28,668 --> 00:05:31,793
Jesus Christ!
Whose bloody coffin is this?!

33
00:05:31,834 --> 00:05:34,376
Christ, it's heavy!
Hold it!

34
00:05:34,418 --> 00:05:37,668
Yes, yes. Big coffin, this is!

35
00:05:48,168 --> 00:05:50,126
Fuck them.
We'll just leave 'em behind.

36
00:05:50,168 --> 00:05:51,668
It's what they fuckin' want.

37
00:05:51,709 --> 00:05:53,251
A pox on you!

38
00:05:53,293 --> 00:05:55,668
Oh, I like that! Very good.

39
00:05:55,709 --> 00:05:58,043
Leave 'em and be lynched for
the pleasure. That is sweet.

40
00:05:58,084 --> 00:05:59,584
It's a bit rough out there.

41
00:05:59,626 --> 00:06:01,876
Could be they can't get through
to you in this weather.

42
00:06:03,293 --> 00:06:04,793
Do you have things for shelter?

43
00:06:07,376 --> 00:06:09,668
She says thank you.

44
00:06:16,834 --> 00:06:20,084
Does your mother prefer
to come on with us to Nelson?

45
00:06:27,501 --> 00:06:29,084
She says no.

46
00:06:29,126 --> 00:06:31,751
She says she would rather be
boiled alive by natives

47
00:06:31,793 --> 00:06:34,293
than get back on your
stinkin' tub.

48
00:06:34,334 --> 00:06:35,834
You be damn fortuned

49
00:06:35,876 --> 00:06:38,668
I don't smack your puppy gob,
young missy!

50
00:06:40,293 --> 00:06:41,793
Damn lucky!

51
00:06:49,251 --> 00:06:50,751
We're all ready now, sir.

52
00:07:50,959 --> 00:07:53,751
Mother, watch out!

53
00:07:53,793 --> 00:07:55,793
Oh, hell! Are they alright?

54
00:07:55,834 --> 00:07:57,543
Here.

55
00:08:08,834 --> 00:08:10,876
Look. I'm a very big moth.

56
00:08:12,418 --> 00:08:13,918
Will it catch fire?

57
00:08:21,959 --> 00:08:23,876
Mmm.

58
00:08:40,334 --> 00:08:42,584
I'm not gonna call him 'Papa'.

59
00:08:42,626 --> 00:08:44,709
I'm not gonna call him
anything.

60
00:08:44,751 --> 00:08:46,584
I'm not even gonna look at him.

61
00:09:43,626 --> 00:09:45,126
Are we stopping?

62
00:09:51,834 --> 00:09:53,334
Shall we stop?

63
00:10:18,001 --> 00:10:19,543
We must get on.

64
00:10:21,459 --> 00:10:22,959
Hmm?

65
00:10:55,876 --> 00:10:58,001
Miss McGrath?
Alisdair Stewart.

66
00:10:58,043 --> 00:10:59,584
You'll have to wake yourself.

67
00:10:59,626 --> 00:11:02,251
I've got men here
to carry your things.

68
00:11:21,584 --> 00:11:23,376
Well, I see you've got
a good many boxes.

69
00:11:24,876 --> 00:11:26,376
I'd like to know
what's in each...

70
00:11:30,376 --> 00:11:32,001
Can you hear me?!

71
00:11:37,918 --> 00:11:39,501
Oh, well, that's good.

72
00:11:39,543 --> 00:11:41,043
Yes, that's good.

73
00:11:42,501 --> 00:11:44,001
What's in this one?

74
00:11:52,668 --> 00:11:54,959
You're small.
I never thought you'd be small.

75
00:11:58,501 --> 00:12:00,001
And...and this one?

76
00:12:01,459 --> 00:12:03,084
Very large.

77
00:12:06,709 --> 00:12:08,834
What's in it, then? A bedstead?

78
00:12:10,376 --> 00:12:12,209
It's my mother's piano.

79
00:12:14,334 --> 00:12:16,543
Baines, tell them
to carry in pairs.

80
00:12:16,584 --> 00:12:18,334
Take all the boxes...

81
00:12:19,376 --> 00:12:21,168
..the table, and, uh...

82
00:12:21,209 --> 00:12:22,709
..the suitcases.

83
00:12:24,834 --> 00:12:26,334
What do you think?

84
00:12:29,876 --> 00:12:31,459
She looks tired.

85
00:12:33,793 --> 00:12:35,584
She's stunted.
That's one thing.

86
00:12:39,459 --> 00:12:41,293
The big crate?
No, no.

87
00:12:41,334 --> 00:12:44,751
Just the trunks and the boxes,
as I explained.

88
00:13:01,501 --> 00:13:04,001
No, no. It can't come now.
It must.

89
00:13:04,043 --> 00:13:05,876
She wants it to come.

90
00:13:05,918 --> 00:13:07,501
Yes, and so do I,

91
00:13:07,543 --> 00:13:09,876
but there are too few of us
here to carry it now.

92
00:13:10,918 --> 00:13:12,418
Too heavy.

93
00:13:15,501 --> 00:13:17,168
Do you mean you don't
want your clothing

94
00:13:17,209 --> 00:13:18,668
or your kitchenware to come?

95
00:13:18,709 --> 00:13:20,209
Is that what you mean?

96
00:13:24,293 --> 00:13:26,626
We can't leave the piano!

97
00:13:28,709 --> 00:13:31,251
Look, let's not discuss
this any further.

98
00:13:31,293 --> 00:13:32,959
I'm very pleased
that you arrived safely...

99
00:13:33,001 --> 00:13:34,376
Mother wants to know

100
00:13:34,418 --> 00:13:36,918
if they could come back
directly for it.

101
00:13:36,959 --> 00:13:39,459
Could I apologise for the
delay, which I regret was...

102
00:13:39,501 --> 00:13:42,168
After they've taken
the other things.

103
00:13:53,543 --> 00:13:55,668
Might I suggest
that you prepare yourself

104
00:13:55,709 --> 00:13:57,668
for a difficult journey?

105
00:13:57,709 --> 00:14:01,709
The bush will tear clothing and
the mud is very deep in places.

106
00:14:04,334 --> 00:14:06,209
Hey, Stewart!

107
00:14:08,709 --> 00:14:10,084
What do they think
they're doing?

108
00:14:10,126 --> 00:14:11,626
We don't have time for this!

109
00:14:13,251 --> 00:14:14,959
Baines!

110
00:15:49,501 --> 00:15:51,376
What's the matter?
Why are they stopping?

111
00:15:53,834 --> 00:15:56,709
That's the way to
the burial ground. It's tapu.

112
00:15:56,751 --> 00:15:59,084
But we came down this way.
I'm sure we did.

113
00:16:01,876 --> 00:16:03,418
They want more money.
That's all it is.

114
00:16:03,459 --> 00:16:05,543
They're trying to make
two days out of it.

115
00:16:05,584 --> 00:16:07,168
No.

116
00:16:08,501 --> 00:16:11,793
No, they know another track -
to the side of this.

117
00:16:24,209 --> 00:16:27,376
Septimus! Now, take that off!
Take that off!

118
00:16:27,418 --> 00:16:29,084
Watch your feet!

119
00:16:29,126 --> 00:16:30,751
Oh, watch your feet!

120
00:16:30,793 --> 00:16:33,293
Stop, Septimus! Please stop it!

121
00:16:33,334 --> 00:16:35,001
Stop it!
Stop it!

122
00:16:36,709 --> 00:16:38,459
Oh, Septimus, stop it, please.

123
00:16:38,501 --> 00:16:40,001
Oh, you'll tear it!

124
00:16:40,043 --> 00:16:42,126
Oh, the tag's broken.

125
00:16:42,168 --> 00:16:45,043
Septimus, now stop it.

126
00:16:47,668 --> 00:16:49,959
Oh, you'll tear it! Be careful!

127
00:16:50,001 --> 00:16:51,709
Arm down.

128
00:16:53,584 --> 00:16:55,501
If you cannot have
a ceremony together,

129
00:16:55,543 --> 00:16:57,293
you have at least a photograph.

130
00:17:08,376 --> 00:17:10,751
Careful. The lace
is most fragile.

131
00:17:10,793 --> 00:17:14,001
My real father was
a famous German composer.

132
00:17:17,126 --> 00:17:20,626
They met when my mother was
an opera singer in Luxembourg.

133
00:17:22,918 --> 00:17:24,418
Why?

134
00:17:27,709 --> 00:17:30,084
I want to be in the photograph.

135
00:17:34,376 --> 00:17:36,459
Will we leave the cloth
here for the photograph?

136
00:17:36,501 --> 00:17:39,043
No, no. It is just
to keep the chair dry.

137
00:17:39,084 --> 00:17:42,959
Ah, here they are.
How beautiful.

138
00:17:42,959 --> 00:17:44,584
I almost slipped
on the planks, Uncle.

139
00:17:44,626 --> 00:17:46,209
They've gotten very greasy.

140
00:17:46,251 --> 00:17:48,751
Aye, you use the left chair.
Pull the tarpaulin.

141
00:17:49,834 --> 00:17:52,959
I am sorry for the rain.
Pity I'm not lighted up inside.

142
00:17:54,334 --> 00:17:57,001
Shower for
a spring...for a spring bride.

143
00:17:58,084 --> 00:18:00,001
Shall I hold the umbrella
on this side, or t'other?

144
00:18:00,043 --> 00:18:01,918
On t'other, on t'other.
Move over!

145
00:18:01,959 --> 00:18:03,959
Can you take this, please?

146
00:18:04,001 --> 00:18:06,543
And...sitting!

147
00:18:10,334 --> 00:18:13,668
Uh...very still.

148
00:18:16,459 --> 00:18:18,376
And where did they get married?

149
00:18:18,418 --> 00:18:22,084
In an enormous forest, with
real fairies as bridesmaids,

150
00:18:22,126 --> 00:18:24,168
each holding
a little elf's hand.

151
00:18:25,501 --> 00:18:27,543
No. I tell a lie.

152
00:18:27,584 --> 00:18:30,543
It was in a small country
church in the mountains.

153
00:18:30,584 --> 00:18:32,084
Which mountains
are those, dear?

154
00:18:32,126 --> 00:18:34,209
The Pyrenees.
Oh.

155
00:18:34,251 --> 00:18:35,876
I've never been there.

156
00:18:35,918 --> 00:18:37,834
Mother used to sing
the songs in German,

157
00:18:37,876 --> 00:18:41,043
and her voice would echo
across the valleys.

158
00:18:41,084 --> 00:18:42,959
That was before the accident.

159
00:18:43,001 --> 00:18:45,668
And what happened?

160
00:18:45,709 --> 00:18:48,001
One day,
when my mother and father

161
00:18:48,043 --> 00:18:50,043
were singing together
in the forest,

162
00:18:50,084 --> 00:18:52,709
a great storm blew up
out of nowhere.

163
00:18:52,751 --> 00:18:54,584
But so passionate
was their singing

164
00:18:54,626 --> 00:18:56,126
that they did not notice,

165
00:18:56,168 --> 00:18:58,501
nor did they stop
as the rain began to fall.

166
00:18:58,543 --> 00:19:01,668
And when their voices rose
for the final bars of the duet,

167
00:19:01,709 --> 00:19:03,043
a great bolt of lightning...

168
00:19:04,459 --> 00:19:06,334
..came out of the sky
and struck my father

169
00:19:06,376 --> 00:19:08,293
so that he lit up like a torch.

170
00:19:08,334 --> 00:19:11,418
And at the same moment
my father was struck dead,

171
00:19:11,459 --> 00:19:13,501
my mother was struck dumb!

172
00:19:13,543 --> 00:19:16,376
She never spoke another word.

173
00:19:19,876 --> 00:19:21,751
Oh, dear.

174
00:19:23,293 --> 00:19:25,293
Oh...

175
00:19:25,334 --> 00:19:27,501
Not another word?

176
00:19:29,584 --> 00:19:31,584
Oh, from the shock, yes.

177
00:19:31,626 --> 00:19:33,584
It would be.

178
00:19:33,626 --> 00:19:35,543
Terrible. Terrible.

179
00:19:36,793 --> 00:19:38,876
Oh, dear!

180
00:19:38,918 --> 00:19:41,959
Oh!Terrible.

181
00:19:42,001 --> 00:19:43,709
Terrible.

182
00:19:45,501 --> 00:19:47,084
There, there, d...

183
00:19:47,126 --> 00:19:48,626
Dear!

184
00:20:40,251 --> 00:20:42,418
I'm sorry.

185
00:20:46,918 --> 00:20:47,959
Um...

186
00:20:48,001 --> 00:20:52,793
I have to go away
for some days.

187
00:20:52,834 --> 00:20:54,834
There's some Maori land
I'm interested in

188
00:20:54,876 --> 00:20:57,876
which I...may buy
very reasonably.

189
00:21:01,293 --> 00:21:04,459
Well, I hope you'll spend
the time to get settled in

190
00:21:04,501 --> 00:21:07,418
and perhaps...in some ways...

191
00:21:09,168 --> 00:21:10,668
..we could start again.

192
00:21:12,293 --> 00:21:13,793
Alright?

193
00:22:27,293 --> 00:22:29,126
I'm not able to read.

194
00:22:39,626 --> 00:22:43,001
Please take us back to
the beach where we landed.

195
00:22:48,334 --> 00:22:51,001
I am sorry. I can't do that.

196
00:22:53,209 --> 00:22:54,876
I don't have the time.

197
00:22:57,834 --> 00:22:59,334
Goodbye.

198
00:23:32,709 --> 00:23:34,584
I can't take you there.

199
00:23:36,668 --> 00:23:38,209
I can't do it.

200
00:23:47,876 --> 00:23:50,626
Whoa. Whoa.

201
00:24:45,918 --> 00:24:49,418
Mumma! Mumma!
Watch me! Watch!

202
00:25:03,376 --> 00:25:05,543
Mumma! Mumma!

203
00:27:17,959 --> 00:27:19,709
Hello there.

204
00:27:19,751 --> 00:27:21,251
Hello.

205
00:27:46,751 --> 00:27:48,751
Well, you've stopped
combing your hair,

206
00:27:48,793 --> 00:27:50,876
which is a good thing.
It was looking overdone.

207
00:27:52,168 --> 00:27:54,918
You see, these are the slits
that the heads will go through.

208
00:27:54,959 --> 00:27:56,959
Show him, Nessie.
Slits.

209
00:27:57,001 --> 00:28:00,418
They'll be dead. The reverend's
going to use animal blood.

210
00:28:00,459 --> 00:28:01,959
No doubt it'll be
very dramatic.

211
00:28:02,001 --> 00:28:04,376
Be very dramatic.
Tea!

212
00:28:11,001 --> 00:28:12,876
Morag...

213
00:28:12,918 --> 00:28:14,876
..what would you think

214
00:28:14,918 --> 00:28:17,959
if someone...
were to play a kitchen table...

215
00:28:19,376 --> 00:28:20,876
..like it were a piano?

216
00:28:23,084 --> 00:28:25,001
Like it were a piano?

217
00:28:25,043 --> 00:28:26,626
Yes. It's strange, isn't it?

218
00:28:26,668 --> 00:28:29,501
I mean, it's not a piano.
It's...

219
00:28:31,084 --> 00:28:32,959
It doesn't make any sound.

220
00:28:33,001 --> 00:28:35,209
Biscuits!

221
00:28:36,584 --> 00:28:39,418
- No. No sound.
- I mean...

222
00:28:42,084 --> 00:28:44,251
..I knew she was mute, but...

223
00:28:44,293 --> 00:28:47,001
..now I'm thinking
perhaps it's more than that.

224
00:28:47,043 --> 00:28:48,876
I'm wondering if she's not...

225
00:28:48,918 --> 00:28:50,418
..brain-affected.

226
00:28:50,459 --> 00:28:51,793
Shush!

227
00:28:53,418 --> 00:28:55,334
No sound at all?

228
00:28:55,376 --> 00:28:56,876
Well, no. It was a table.

229
00:28:58,418 --> 00:29:00,584
Well, she was very violent
with the gown.

230
00:29:00,626 --> 00:29:02,876
She tore off a chunk of lace.

231
00:29:04,543 --> 00:29:06,626
If I hadn't been there
to see it,

232
00:29:06,668 --> 00:29:08,459
I'd have sworn she'd have
used her teeth and...

233
00:29:08,501 --> 00:29:10,001
Wiped her feet on it.

234
00:29:13,793 --> 00:29:15,584
Well, it hasn't come
to anything yet. It's...

235
00:29:17,001 --> 00:29:18,834
..simply a concern, that's all.

236
00:29:18,876 --> 00:29:20,168
Yes.

237
00:29:20,209 --> 00:29:21,918
Yes, of course, a concern.

238
00:29:25,001 --> 00:29:27,001
There's something to be said
for silence.

239
00:29:27,043 --> 00:29:28,793
Indeed.

240
00:29:28,834 --> 00:29:30,376
Cotton!

241
00:29:32,418 --> 00:29:35,584
And, with time,
I'm sure she'll become...

242
00:29:35,626 --> 00:29:37,584
..affectionate.

243
00:29:37,626 --> 00:29:40,918
Certainly there's nothing
so easy to like as a pet,

244
00:29:40,959 --> 00:29:42,709
and they're quite silent.

245
00:29:43,876 --> 00:29:45,751
♪ And when
they were up, they were up

246
00:29:45,793 --> 00:29:47,293
♪ And when were down,
they were down

247
00:29:47,334 --> 00:29:49,043
♪ And when they were
only halfway up

248
00:29:49,084 --> 00:29:50,668
♪ They were neither up nor down

249
00:29:50,709 --> 00:29:52,584
♪ The grand old Duke of York

250
00:29:52,626 --> 00:29:54,126
♪ He had 10,000 men

251
00:29:54,168 --> 00:29:56,168
♪ He marched them up
to the top of the hill

252
00:29:56,209 --> 00:29:58,001
♪ And he marched them
down again... ♪

253
00:29:59,959 --> 00:30:02,251
Those 80 acres
across the stream.

254
00:30:02,293 --> 00:30:03,668
What do you think of them?

255
00:30:04,918 --> 00:30:06,334
I don't have any money.

256
00:30:06,376 --> 00:30:08,001
What are you on about?

257
00:30:08,043 --> 00:30:10,376
I'd like to make a swap.

258
00:30:10,418 --> 00:30:12,834
What for?

259
00:30:12,876 --> 00:30:14,376
The piano.

260
00:30:17,709 --> 00:30:19,209
What, the piano on the beach?

261
00:30:26,334 --> 00:30:27,918
It's not marshy, is it?

262
00:30:29,459 --> 00:30:31,043
No.

263
00:30:37,959 --> 00:30:40,501
Well, Baines the music lover.
I never would have thought.

264
00:30:41,876 --> 00:30:43,543
Hidden talents, George?

265
00:30:47,668 --> 00:30:49,584
I'd have to get lessons.

266
00:30:49,626 --> 00:30:52,001
It wouldn't be much use
without them.

267
00:30:53,293 --> 00:30:54,793
Oh, yes, I suppose you would.

268
00:30:59,334 --> 00:31:00,834
Well, Ada can play.

269
00:31:02,334 --> 00:31:04,168
I have in a letter
that she plays very well.

270
00:31:04,209 --> 00:31:06,126
She's been playing
since she was five or six.

271
00:31:15,584 --> 00:31:17,084
What on?

272
00:31:17,084 --> 00:31:20,709
Well, on your piano.
That's the swap.

273
00:31:24,418 --> 00:31:25,918
What'd she say?

274
00:31:25,959 --> 00:31:29,084
She says it's her piano and
she won't have him touch it!

275
00:31:32,043 --> 00:31:34,501
He's an oaf. He can't read.
He's ignorant.

276
00:31:35,834 --> 00:31:37,501
Well, he wants
to improve himself.

277
00:31:38,626 --> 00:31:40,293
And you'll be able to play it.

278
00:31:46,584 --> 00:31:48,418
Teach him how to look after it!

279
00:31:57,584 --> 00:31:59,084
You can't go on like this.

280
00:32:00,709 --> 00:32:04,126
We're a family now. We all make
sacrifices and <i>so will you!</i>

281
00:32:05,584 --> 00:32:07,834
You will teach him.

282
00:32:07,876 --> 00:32:09,376
And I will see to it!

283
00:32:51,918 --> 00:32:54,459
Ah! A Broadwood.

284
00:32:54,501 --> 00:32:56,793
Oh, a fine instrument.

285
00:32:56,834 --> 00:32:59,959
I've not seen one here.

286
00:33:00,001 --> 00:33:02,959
Nor in New South Wales,
where I've tuned some 200.

287
00:33:03,001 --> 00:33:05,876
Yes, they like
their pianos there.

288
00:33:14,793 --> 00:33:16,918
Scent.

289
00:33:18,626 --> 00:33:20,376
And salt, of course.

290
00:34:19,834 --> 00:34:22,084
Mother says she can't stand
to teach piano

291
00:34:22,126 --> 00:34:23,918
with it all out of tune,

292
00:34:23,959 --> 00:34:26,001
so I'm to do scales.

293
00:34:30,793 --> 00:34:33,043
I hope you scrubbed your hands.

294
00:34:36,626 --> 00:34:38,251
Ooh. It's in tune.

295
00:34:51,751 --> 00:34:53,501
It's in tune!

296
00:34:56,793 --> 00:34:58,293
I was teaching!

297
00:35:16,626 --> 00:35:19,584
Mother would like to see
what you can play.

298
00:35:19,626 --> 00:35:21,876
I'd rather...not play.

299
00:35:23,334 --> 00:35:25,876
I want to listen
and learn that way.

300
00:35:25,918 --> 00:35:28,251
Everyone has to practise.

301
00:35:30,709 --> 00:35:33,251
I just want to listen.

302
00:35:57,084 --> 00:35:58,418
Lovely.

303
00:36:33,376 --> 00:36:37,209
Oh, but tell me again!

304
00:36:37,251 --> 00:36:38,918
Was he a teacher?

305
00:36:40,459 --> 00:36:42,293
How did you speak to him?

306
00:36:57,959 --> 00:37:01,418
What happened?
Why didn't you get married?

307
00:37:17,834 --> 00:37:19,543
Shall I kiss you goodnight?

308
00:37:35,376 --> 00:37:38,168
Get out! You need a bath!

309
00:37:38,209 --> 00:37:41,168
Go on! Out! Bad dog!

310
00:37:41,209 --> 00:37:45,501
Boo! Go on, you're dirty!
Bad, smelly dog!

311
00:37:45,543 --> 00:37:48,126
Move it, Flynn!

312
00:38:06,376 --> 00:38:08,959
Ada, wait. Wait.

313
00:38:09,001 --> 00:38:12,043
Do you know how...to bargain?

314
00:38:14,043 --> 00:38:15,918
There's a way you can have
your piano back.

315
00:38:17,293 --> 00:38:18,959
Do you want it back?

316
00:38:20,793 --> 00:38:22,293
Do you want it back?

317
00:38:28,626 --> 00:38:30,209
You see...

318
00:38:32,376 --> 00:38:34,293
..I'd like us to make a deal.

319
00:38:37,043 --> 00:38:39,084
There's...things I'd...

320
00:38:41,543 --> 00:38:43,959
..like to do while you play.

321
00:38:44,001 --> 00:38:45,959
If you let me,
you can earn it back.

322
00:38:46,001 --> 00:38:48,418
What do you think?

323
00:38:48,459 --> 00:38:50,084
One visit for every key.

324
00:39:11,543 --> 00:39:12,668
Your dress?

325
00:39:14,584 --> 00:39:16,084
Skirt?

326
00:39:19,918 --> 00:39:21,209
For every black one?

327
00:39:23,293 --> 00:39:25,293
That's a lot less. Half.

328
00:39:26,293 --> 00:39:28,293
Alright. Alright.

329
00:39:28,334 --> 00:39:29,876
Then the black keys.

330
00:39:43,793 --> 00:39:46,168
Poor baby.

331
00:39:46,209 --> 00:39:51,876
What horrid little person
put you in the rain

332
00:39:51,918 --> 00:39:54,209
and shoved you with a stick?

333
00:39:54,251 --> 00:39:56,251
Hmm, baby? Hmm?

334
00:39:56,293 --> 00:39:58,459
Hmm?

335
00:39:58,501 --> 00:40:00,918
You're alright with moi.

336
00:40:04,334 --> 00:40:05,834
Scissors.

337
00:40:06,876 --> 00:40:08,209
Thank you.

338
00:40:08,251 --> 00:40:12,959
Nessie, put that down and
come and put your hand out.

339
00:40:13,001 --> 00:40:16,126
Oh, no. Please, Mr Stewart...

340
00:40:16,168 --> 00:40:17,543
No, no, no.
Nessie, please.

341
00:40:17,584 --> 00:40:19,084
Go on, Nessie.
She's timid.

342
00:40:19,126 --> 00:40:21,334
Alright, Mary, come along.
Down here.

343
00:40:23,501 --> 00:40:25,001
Well, come on, girl!
Get a move on!

344
00:40:25,043 --> 00:40:26,751
Oh! Alright, then.

345
00:40:30,376 --> 00:40:32,918
Down here. Put out your hand.

346
00:40:34,043 --> 00:40:35,543
Now...

347
00:40:38,334 --> 00:40:41,418
No, no. Put out your hand here.

348
00:40:43,126 --> 00:40:44,626
Now...

349
00:40:48,293 --> 00:40:50,751
No, no. Look, look.
You're being attacked.

350
00:40:55,001 --> 00:40:57,084
No. Come on, come on.
There you go.

351
00:41:00,876 --> 00:41:04,251
And with the blood,
it will be a very good effect.

352
00:41:04,293 --> 00:41:06,251
Here, Flynn. Here, Flynn.

353
00:41:06,293 --> 00:41:08,376
Here, Flynn. Flynn! Flynn!

354
00:41:08,418 --> 00:41:10,501
Flynn! Here, Flynn.

355
00:41:10,543 --> 00:41:12,959
Bad boy. Here, wee boy.

356
00:41:13,001 --> 00:41:14,626
Bad, bad boy.

357
00:41:14,668 --> 00:41:16,126
Flynn!

358
00:41:16,168 --> 00:41:18,543
Flynn, don't be trouble.

359
00:41:18,584 --> 00:41:21,459
Flynn! Flynn.

360
00:41:33,084 --> 00:41:35,376
I want to speak to my mother.

361
00:41:42,001 --> 00:41:45,251
I don't want to be outside.
I want to watch.

362
00:41:50,376 --> 00:41:51,876
I'll be very quiet.

363
00:41:58,834 --> 00:42:00,334
I won't look at him.

364
00:44:36,668 --> 00:44:38,918
- Be very careful.
- Careful.

365
00:44:42,209 --> 00:44:45,334
I hardly need to give one to
you, but here you are anyway.

366
00:44:46,918 --> 00:44:48,543
Don't be late.

367
00:44:48,584 --> 00:44:50,751
You will see
that there are two times,

368
00:44:50,793 --> 00:44:53,001
and since you are
accompanying a performer,

369
00:44:53,043 --> 00:44:54,793
you will need to make
the earlier time.

370
00:44:56,668 --> 00:44:58,168
Wait!

371
00:45:02,709 --> 00:45:04,668
How are the lessons going?

372
00:45:09,501 --> 00:45:11,084
He's getting on alright,
then, is he?

373
00:45:15,418 --> 00:45:17,293
She seems quietened down.

374
00:45:17,334 --> 00:45:19,043
Is she more affectionate?

375
00:45:22,751 --> 00:45:24,209
Oh, well.

376
00:45:24,251 --> 00:45:26,293
Slowly. Slowly.

377
00:45:32,084 --> 00:45:34,293
Lift your skirt.

378
00:45:51,459 --> 00:45:53,001
Lift it higher.

379
00:46:14,459 --> 00:46:16,001
Higher.

380
00:46:19,751 --> 00:46:21,918
Higher!

381
00:46:23,084 --> 00:46:25,209
Lift it higher.

382
00:47:24,834 --> 00:47:26,959
You no worry, Baine.

383
00:47:27,001 --> 00:47:29,209
I save you.

384
00:47:29,251 --> 00:47:30,543
I have a wife.

385
00:47:30,584 --> 00:47:32,876
I save her too.

386
00:47:40,834 --> 00:47:42,251
Where's your wife?

387
00:47:42,293 --> 00:47:43,793
My wife?

388
00:47:45,001 --> 00:47:46,959
Oh, she has a life of her own.

389
00:47:47,001 --> 00:47:48,293
In Hull, England.

390
00:47:48,334 --> 00:47:50,459
Must be ugly

391
00:47:50,501 --> 00:47:52,918
for you to run away.

392
00:47:52,959 --> 00:47:54,626
You need another wife.

393
00:48:05,584 --> 00:48:07,293
Undo your dress.

394
00:48:08,834 --> 00:48:10,334
I want to see your arms.

395
00:48:40,626 --> 00:48:42,168
Play.

396
00:49:07,001 --> 00:49:08,709
Two keys.

397
00:50:02,793 --> 00:50:06,959
"I shall listen hard
at rehearsal

398
00:50:07,001 --> 00:50:09,668
"because I live too far
to come often."

399
00:50:10,959 --> 00:50:12,584
Which sign is the word
'rehearsal'?

400
00:50:16,668 --> 00:50:20,251
I can't imagine a fate
worse than being dumb.

401
00:50:22,126 --> 00:50:23,793
To be deaf.

402
00:50:23,834 --> 00:50:25,959
Oh, aye. Deaf too.

403
00:50:26,001 --> 00:50:27,793
Terrible. Awful.

404
00:50:27,834 --> 00:50:31,126
Actually, to tell you
the whole truth,

405
00:50:31,168 --> 00:50:33,459
Mother says most people
speak rubbish

406
00:50:33,501 --> 00:50:35,251
and it's not worth the listen.

407
00:50:37,209 --> 00:50:39,543
Well, that is a strong opinion.

408
00:50:39,584 --> 00:50:42,043
Aye. It's unholy.

409
00:51:01,709 --> 00:51:03,459
What do they say?
Are they selling?

410
00:51:06,751 --> 00:51:08,918
Offer the blankets
for <i>half</i> the land.

411
00:51:13,168 --> 00:51:15,459
12.

412
00:51:18,751 --> 00:51:20,168
The guns, Baines.
Offer the guns.

413
00:51:25,709 --> 00:51:28,709
What do they want the land for?
They don't do anything with it.

414
00:51:28,751 --> 00:51:31,418
They don't cultivate it, they
don't burn it back, nothing.

415
00:51:33,418 --> 00:51:36,459
I mean, how do they even know
that it's theirs?

416
00:51:38,501 --> 00:51:40,001
Um...

417
00:51:42,918 --> 00:51:46,376
I thought I might as well mark
it out, you know? As we agreed.

418
00:51:46,418 --> 00:51:48,001
Yes. Why not?

419
00:51:51,459 --> 00:51:55,668
Well, Ada says you're doing
well with the piano.

420
00:51:56,918 --> 00:51:58,543
I'll have to come
and hear you play.

421
00:52:00,293 --> 00:52:01,834
What do you play?

422
00:52:01,876 --> 00:52:03,459
Nothing just yet.

423
00:52:03,501 --> 00:52:05,001
No?

424
00:52:49,543 --> 00:52:51,084
Ah!

425
00:52:58,209 --> 00:53:00,626
Ada, four keys.

426
00:53:00,668 --> 00:53:02,001
Why five?

427
00:53:02,043 --> 00:53:03,668
I just want to lie.

428
00:53:07,001 --> 00:53:08,626
Alright. Alright. Five.

429
00:54:26,959 --> 00:54:30,584
♪ Early
in the month of May

430
00:54:30,626 --> 00:54:35,043
♪ The angels were
sweetly singing

431
00:54:35,084 --> 00:54:39,543
♪ A young man
on his deathbed lay

432
00:54:39,584 --> 00:54:43,709
♪ For love of Barbara Allen. ♪

433
00:54:52,584 --> 00:54:54,418
Take it easy.

434
00:54:54,459 --> 00:54:57,126
Here, mind that hole now.
Steady.

435
00:54:57,168 --> 00:55:00,543
Hang on. Alright. There you go.

436
00:55:02,334 --> 00:55:06,376
How are you, then? So, will you
marry me next week?

437
00:55:09,209 --> 00:55:10,793
Just put your arm around me.

438
00:55:10,834 --> 00:55:12,709
That's right, love.
That's the way.

439
00:55:14,334 --> 00:55:16,668
Oh, come on!
We're running late.

440
00:55:16,709 --> 00:55:18,543
If you haven't got
your lip colour on,

441
00:55:18,584 --> 00:55:20,918
can you line up behind Rose,
please?

442
00:55:22,584 --> 00:55:24,293
Have you all been
to the lavatory?

443
00:55:24,334 --> 00:55:25,834
Yes.

444
00:55:31,168 --> 00:55:33,293
I want no running
on the stage.

445
00:55:36,584 --> 00:55:38,918
They're bringing in
extra chairs!

446
00:55:43,584 --> 00:55:47,043
Do not touch the blood.
And look who's here, hmm?

447
00:55:47,084 --> 00:55:49,626
The musical Mr Baines.

448
00:55:49,668 --> 00:55:52,959
Whoa! What are you going to
play for us tonight?

449
00:55:53,001 --> 00:55:54,626
'Twinkle Twinkle', eh, George?

450
00:55:54,668 --> 00:55:57,293
How about a little tinkle,
tinkle, George?

451
00:56:00,293 --> 00:56:02,918
Perhaps you would like
to turn the pages for Nessie.

452
00:56:02,959 --> 00:56:04,459
She's playing for the children.

453
00:56:07,793 --> 00:56:09,501
I'm in costume.

454
00:56:11,918 --> 00:56:14,376
I'm very pleased
you've taken up the piano.

455
00:56:14,418 --> 00:56:16,501
Now, where's this song?

456
00:56:38,126 --> 00:56:40,001
George? Excuse me.

457
00:56:40,043 --> 00:56:41,876
How about
'Mary Had a Little Lamb'?

458
00:56:41,918 --> 00:56:43,293
"Baaaaa!"

459
00:56:43,334 --> 00:56:46,709
Or a polka? Come on, George,
what's it to be, hmm?

460
00:56:46,751 --> 00:56:48,626
Fools.

461
00:56:50,543 --> 00:56:52,501
Come on, George. Move along.

462
00:56:54,334 --> 00:56:55,918
Ladies and gentlemen,

463
00:56:55,959 --> 00:56:58,334
could you take
your seats, please?

464
00:56:58,376 --> 00:56:59,876
We're about to begin.

465
00:57:13,043 --> 00:57:16,834
♪ Early in
the month of May

466
00:57:16,876 --> 00:57:20,251
♪ The angels were
sweetly singing

467
00:57:20,293 --> 00:57:25,168
♪ A young man
on his deathbed lay

468
00:57:25,209 --> 00:57:29,459
♪ For love of Barbara Allen

469
00:57:29,501 --> 00:57:34,418
♪ Out of his ground,
a red rose bush

470
00:57:34,459 --> 00:57:38,043
♪ And out of hers, a briar

471
00:57:38,084 --> 00:57:42,293
♪ Then they grew up
to the high church wall

472
00:57:42,334 --> 00:57:47,084
♪ Till they could go no higher

473
00:57:47,126 --> 00:57:51,584
♪ And back they came
in a true love's knot

474
00:57:51,626 --> 00:57:55,584
♪ Red roses and sweet briar. ♪

475
00:58:01,293 --> 00:58:03,584
And so the young maid

476
00:58:03,626 --> 00:58:08,418
came upon each and all
of Bluebeard's missing wives,

477
00:58:08,459 --> 00:58:12,709
their severed heads
still bleeding,

478
00:58:12,751 --> 00:58:15,959
their eyes still crying.

479
00:58:17,251 --> 00:58:19,584
Slow down, Nessie!
Slow down!

480
00:58:19,626 --> 00:58:21,209
But hush!

481
00:58:21,209 --> 00:58:23,376
Who comes?

482
00:58:26,626 --> 00:58:31,293
I'm home early,
my sweet wife!

483
00:58:31,334 --> 00:58:33,126
Where art thou?

484
00:58:33,168 --> 00:58:38,168
Oh, husband! What a surprise!

485
00:58:38,209 --> 00:58:43,293
Yes, wife. A surprise indeed.

486
00:58:43,334 --> 00:58:46,418
So, now you know my secret!

487
00:58:46,459 --> 00:58:49,043
No! No!

488
00:58:49,084 --> 00:58:53,334
You, the youngest...

489
00:58:53,376 --> 00:58:57,209
..and sweetest...
No!

490
00:58:57,251 --> 00:58:59,293
..of all my wives...

491
00:58:59,293 --> 00:59:01,043
No!

492
00:59:01,084 --> 00:59:04,584
..must be prepared to die!

493
00:59:06,251 --> 00:59:09,334
No! No! Wait!

494
00:59:09,376 --> 00:59:11,418
I shall not wait!

495
00:59:11,459 --> 00:59:13,251
No, please!

496
00:59:13,293 --> 00:59:16,043
Bare your neck!

497
00:59:29,084 --> 00:59:30,459
Help! They're mad!

498
00:59:38,918 --> 00:59:43,334
This is the animal
blood. This is the axe, Chief.

499
00:59:43,376 --> 00:59:46,959
Now, I'd like to introduce you.
This is Mrs Williams.

500
00:59:47,001 --> 00:59:48,751
This is Mrs Parsons.

501
00:59:48,793 --> 00:59:50,334
This...

502
00:59:50,376 --> 00:59:53,543
This is Mrs Reid,
this is Miss Palmer

503
00:59:53,584 --> 00:59:55,084
and this is Miss Kerr.

504
00:59:58,709 --> 01:00:00,501
That's very, very nice.

505
01:00:15,126 --> 01:00:16,918
Do what you like.

506
01:00:18,334 --> 01:00:20,043
Play what you like.

507
01:01:33,709 --> 01:01:36,334
I want to lie together
without clothes on.

508
01:01:38,834 --> 01:01:40,501
How many would that be?

509
01:01:49,293 --> 01:01:50,959
Yes.

510
01:01:51,001 --> 01:01:52,543
10 keys.

511
01:03:57,668 --> 01:04:00,334
What o'clock say, Mr Stewart?

512
01:04:00,376 --> 01:04:02,918
Got tupeka, Mr Stewart?
Time for your puff-puff.

513
01:04:07,626 --> 01:04:10,751
Ae. Ae.

514
01:04:14,501 --> 01:04:16,584
Never behave like that.
Never, nowhere.

515
01:04:18,251 --> 01:04:20,126
You're greatly shamed.

516
01:04:20,168 --> 01:04:22,168
You've shamed these trunks.

517
01:04:41,834 --> 01:04:44,168
I know why Mr Baines
can't play the piano.

518
01:04:47,709 --> 01:04:49,209
You missed some here.

519
01:04:52,209 --> 01:04:54,626
She never gives him a turn.

520
01:04:54,668 --> 01:04:57,459
She just plays
what she pleases.

521
01:04:57,501 --> 01:05:00,168
And sometimes
she doesn't play at all.

522
01:05:02,293 --> 01:05:04,168
When's the next lesson?

523
01:05:05,793 --> 01:05:07,293
Tomorrow.

524
01:05:46,084 --> 01:05:48,126
I have given the piano
back to you.

525
01:05:49,501 --> 01:05:51,001
I've had enough.

526
01:05:56,459 --> 01:05:58,084
The arrangement...

527
01:06:00,834 --> 01:06:04,334
..is making you a whore
and me wretched.

528
01:06:06,418 --> 01:06:08,418
I want you to care for me.

529
01:06:10,293 --> 01:06:11,876
But you can't.

530
01:06:20,209 --> 01:06:21,793
It's yours. Leave.

531
01:06:23,376 --> 01:06:24,876
Go on. Go.

532
01:06:42,126 --> 01:06:43,668
Stop right there!

533
01:06:49,084 --> 01:06:51,001
This isn't yours.

534
01:06:51,043 --> 01:06:54,459
What are you doing
with the piano? Hmm?

535
01:06:54,501 --> 01:06:57,543
He's given it to us.

536
01:06:57,584 --> 01:07:00,251
Put that down. Put it down!

537
01:07:03,543 --> 01:07:06,834
You're very cunning, Ada.
I've seen through you.

538
01:07:06,876 --> 01:07:09,251
I'm not going to lose
the land this way.

539
01:07:09,293 --> 01:07:10,793
Stay there!

540
01:07:21,126 --> 01:07:23,793
George don't want to see
nobody. He's sick.

541
01:07:28,084 --> 01:07:30,418
You got the tupeka for Hira?

542
01:07:31,876 --> 01:07:33,376
No.

543
01:07:35,459 --> 01:07:37,126
Much tupeka?

544
01:07:37,168 --> 01:07:38,709
Baines?

545
01:07:41,668 --> 01:07:43,334
Look, Baines.

546
01:07:43,376 --> 01:07:45,168
Baines, look.

547
01:07:45,209 --> 01:07:47,459
I don't think you should have
given up the piano.

548
01:07:48,834 --> 01:07:50,501
I'll make sure that
you're properly taught,

549
01:07:50,543 --> 01:07:53,543
with, you know, music
written on sheets and so on.

550
01:07:53,584 --> 01:07:56,126
I don't want to learn.

551
01:07:56,168 --> 01:07:57,459
You don't want to learn?

552
01:07:57,501 --> 01:07:59,001
No.

553
01:08:02,209 --> 01:08:04,709
Well, what does this do
to our bargain? I mean...

554
01:08:06,168 --> 01:08:08,293
I can't afford the piano,
if you mean me to pay.

555
01:08:10,376 --> 01:08:12,084
No. No payment.

556
01:08:12,084 --> 01:08:13,751
I have given it back.

557
01:08:13,793 --> 01:08:17,501
Well...I'm not sure
that I want it myself.

558
01:08:19,334 --> 01:08:21,418
It was more to your wife
that I gave it.

559
01:08:24,043 --> 01:08:25,876
Oh.

560
01:08:25,918 --> 01:08:27,793
Oh, I...I see.

561
01:08:29,459 --> 01:08:33,043
Well, I expect
she will appreciate it.

562
01:08:42,876 --> 01:08:44,668
I'm afraid this is all I have.

563
01:08:47,001 --> 01:08:48,543
Hey...bring that back!

564
01:09:04,043 --> 01:09:05,543
Is it alright?

565
01:09:08,543 --> 01:09:10,334
Why don't you play something?

566
01:09:14,626 --> 01:09:16,709
What will I play?

567
01:09:19,668 --> 01:09:21,334
Play a jig.

568
01:09:23,001 --> 01:09:24,459
Do I know any jigs?

569
01:09:24,501 --> 01:09:26,709
Play a song, then.

570
01:09:28,584 --> 01:09:32,001
♪ At bughts in the morning

571
01:09:32,043 --> 01:09:36,168
♪ Nae blythe lads are scorning

572
01:09:36,209 --> 01:09:39,709
♪ Lassies are lonely

573
01:09:39,751 --> 01:09:43,668
♪ And dowie and wae

574
01:09:43,709 --> 01:09:47,001
♪ Nae daffin', nae gabbin'

575
01:09:47,043 --> 01:09:50,168
♪ But sighing and sabbing

576
01:09:50,209 --> 01:09:53,084
♪ Ilk ane lifts her leglin

577
01:09:53,126 --> 01:09:56,001
♪ And hies her away. ♪

578
01:10:00,043 --> 01:10:02,543
Why won't she play it?
We get the thing back and...

579
01:10:04,043 --> 01:10:05,543
..she just wanders off.

580
01:10:09,168 --> 01:10:11,168
Well, keep playing.

581
01:10:11,209 --> 01:10:15,209
♪ At bughts in the morning

582
01:10:15,251 --> 01:10:18,876
♪ Na blythe lads are scorning

583
01:10:18,918 --> 01:10:21,959
♪ Lassies are lonely

584
01:10:22,001 --> 01:10:25,459
♪ And dowie and wae... ♪

585
01:12:12,126 --> 01:12:14,126
Wait. Wait!

586
01:12:22,168 --> 01:12:23,751
Why? Why can't I?

587
01:12:30,876 --> 01:12:33,918
I shan't practise
and I don't care!

588
01:12:33,959 --> 01:12:37,001
Blast and damn and bugger her!

589
01:12:37,043 --> 01:12:40,209
Bloody, bloody bugger her!

590
01:12:40,251 --> 01:12:44,709
Let her fall face down
in boiling bloody mud!

591
01:12:44,751 --> 01:12:49,001
Let a spitting mad dog
bite her till she bleeds!

592
01:12:49,043 --> 01:12:51,126
Where's your mother?

593
01:12:52,209 --> 01:12:53,501
Where's she gone?

594
01:12:53,543 --> 01:12:54,793
To hell!

595
01:13:05,251 --> 01:13:07,043
So, what brings you here?

596
01:13:11,834 --> 01:13:13,334
Did you leave something?

597
01:13:15,084 --> 01:13:16,709
Well, I've not found anything.

598
01:13:23,751 --> 01:13:25,334
Does he know something?

599
01:13:38,168 --> 01:13:41,709
The piano was not harmed?
It arrived safely?

600
01:13:47,626 --> 01:13:49,459
Would you like to sit?

601
01:13:51,501 --> 01:13:53,126
I am going to sit.

602
01:14:05,376 --> 01:14:06,876
Ada.

603
01:14:09,876 --> 01:14:11,376
Ada.

604
01:14:13,209 --> 01:14:14,709
I am unhappy.

605
01:14:20,918 --> 01:14:23,918
Because I...want you.

606
01:14:23,959 --> 01:14:25,959
Because my mind
has seized on you

607
01:14:26,001 --> 01:14:27,709
and can think of nothing else.

608
01:14:30,668 --> 01:14:32,293
This is why I suffer.

609
01:14:35,126 --> 01:14:39,584
I...am sick with longing.

610
01:14:39,626 --> 01:14:42,876
I don't eat. I don't sleep.

611
01:14:44,376 --> 01:14:50,793
So if you've come
with no feeling for me,

612
01:14:50,834 --> 01:14:52,334
then go.

613
01:15:01,084 --> 01:15:02,584
Go.

614
01:15:04,126 --> 01:15:05,626
Go.

615
01:15:14,001 --> 01:15:15,626
Get out.

616
01:15:17,334 --> 01:15:18,834
Leave!

617
01:19:04,251 --> 01:19:05,751
What?

618
01:19:08,876 --> 01:19:10,543
Whisper it.

619
01:19:32,209 --> 01:19:34,584
Now you are going,
I am miserable.

620
01:19:34,626 --> 01:19:36,251
Why is that?

621
01:19:38,334 --> 01:19:40,376
Ada, I need to know,
what will you do?

622
01:19:40,418 --> 01:19:42,251
Will you come again?

623
01:19:49,584 --> 01:19:51,126
Wait.

624
01:19:52,168 --> 01:19:54,668
I...don't know
what you're thinking.

625
01:19:56,251 --> 01:19:58,334
Does this mean something
to you? Eh?

626
01:20:02,293 --> 01:20:03,793
I already miss you.

627
01:20:05,876 --> 01:20:07,334
Ada.

628
01:20:08,459 --> 01:20:09,959
Do you love me?

629
01:20:25,168 --> 01:20:29,584
Come tomorrow. If you are
serious, come tomorrow.

630
01:20:42,084 --> 01:20:44,709
Mumma, stay still!

631
01:20:52,626 --> 01:20:54,209
Stay still!

632
01:21:14,418 --> 01:21:16,543
Mmm. Mmm.

633
01:22:40,793 --> 01:22:44,084
Mumma! Mumma!

634
01:22:44,126 --> 01:22:47,293
They're playing your piano!

635
01:22:47,334 --> 01:22:49,293
Mumma!

636
01:23:12,543 --> 01:23:15,001
Here, Papa.

637
01:23:49,126 --> 01:23:51,543
You shouldn't have gone
up there, should you?

638
01:23:53,168 --> 01:23:55,626
I don't like it
and nor does Papa.

639
01:24:03,918 --> 01:24:06,209
We can play cards if you like.

640
01:24:44,293 --> 01:24:46,126
She's asleep. Look.

641
01:24:48,626 --> 01:24:51,043
One night she was found
in her nightgown

642
01:24:51,084 --> 01:24:52,584
on the road to London.

643
01:24:52,626 --> 01:24:54,959
Grandpa said
her feet were cut so badly,

644
01:24:55,001 --> 01:24:56,751
she couldn't walk for a week.

645
01:26:16,126 --> 01:26:17,626
Ada.

646
01:26:46,751 --> 01:26:48,376
Ada.

647
01:26:52,876 --> 01:26:55,001
Alisdair, is it
because of our play?

648
01:26:55,043 --> 01:26:56,918
Have the natives aggressed you?

649
01:26:58,793 --> 01:27:01,543
Well, I have to say, you have
done the wrong thing here.

650
01:27:01,584 --> 01:27:04,418
You have put the latch
on the outside, you see?

651
01:27:06,376 --> 01:27:08,668
Now when you close the door,

652
01:27:08,709 --> 01:27:11,501
it will be the Maoris
that lock you in, you see?

653
01:27:11,543 --> 01:27:14,543
With the latch on that side,
you are quite trapped.

654
01:27:14,584 --> 01:27:16,084
Quite trapped.

655
01:27:16,126 --> 01:27:18,001
We have just come
from George Baines's

656
01:27:18,043 --> 01:27:19,709
and they have taken him over.

657
01:27:19,709 --> 01:27:21,668
It is no wonder he is leaving.

658
01:27:21,709 --> 01:27:23,751
He's got in too deep
with the natives.

659
01:27:23,793 --> 01:27:26,626
They sit on his floor as proud
as kings but without...

660
01:27:26,668 --> 01:27:28,209
A shred of manners.

661
01:27:29,418 --> 01:27:31,084
He's quite altered,

662
01:27:31,126 --> 01:27:33,959
as if they have been trying
some native witchcraft on him.

663
01:27:35,043 --> 01:27:37,876
Well, tomorrow or the day
after, he will be gone.

664
01:27:39,876 --> 01:27:41,543
So Baines
is packing up?

665
01:27:41,584 --> 01:27:44,084
Well, he has nothing to pack,
but he is leaving.

666
01:27:44,126 --> 01:27:46,751
And it is just as well.

667
01:27:46,793 --> 01:27:50,084
Nessie has foolishly grown
an affection for him.

668
01:27:50,126 --> 01:27:52,251
We have had some tears.

669
01:27:53,459 --> 01:27:56,334
Stop it. Stop!

670
01:27:56,376 --> 01:27:58,334
Stop!

671
01:27:59,751 --> 01:28:01,709
I'm quite frightened
of the way back.

672
01:28:01,751 --> 01:28:03,584
We must leave in good light.

673
01:28:03,626 --> 01:28:05,126
Will we be safe?

674
01:28:06,751 --> 01:28:09,251
Oh, yes. If you leave now,
I'm sure of it.

675
01:28:44,168 --> 01:28:45,668
Nessie, hold this.

676
01:28:57,334 --> 01:28:59,459
You know, I am thinking
of the piano.

677
01:29:01,001 --> 01:29:04,043
She does not play the piano
as we do, Nessie.

678
01:29:04,084 --> 01:29:05,751
Up. Up!

679
01:29:10,751 --> 01:29:12,751
No, she is a strange creature.

680
01:29:12,793 --> 01:29:15,334
And her playing is strange,

681
01:29:15,376 --> 01:29:17,668
like a mood
that passes into you.

682
01:29:19,043 --> 01:29:20,543
Up!

683
01:29:24,293 --> 01:29:27,793
Now, your playing is plain and
true, and that is what I like.

684
01:29:27,834 --> 01:29:32,668
To have a sound creep inside
you is not at all pleasant.

685
01:29:32,709 --> 01:29:34,793
What's that?

686
01:29:40,293 --> 01:29:41,834
It's a pigeon, Auntie.

687
01:29:41,876 --> 01:29:43,376
I should have waited!

688
01:30:39,001 --> 01:30:40,584
I want to touch you.

689
01:30:42,418 --> 01:30:44,168
Why can't I touch you?

690
01:30:45,834 --> 01:30:47,376
Don't you like me?

691
01:31:20,834 --> 01:31:24,834
Ooh! Ooh! Come on, Lucky.
Who is gonna be my friend?

692
01:31:24,876 --> 01:31:27,751
I'm coming to catch you
for my big oven!

693
01:31:32,918 --> 01:31:34,584
Whoo!

694
01:31:45,376 --> 01:31:47,376
We must...get on.

695
01:31:51,084 --> 01:31:55,001
I've decided to...
trust you to stay here.

696
01:31:56,293 --> 01:31:57,834
You won't see Baines?

697
01:32:04,918 --> 01:32:06,668
Good.

698
01:32:09,584 --> 01:32:11,084
Good.

699
01:32:12,959 --> 01:32:14,459
And perhaps with time...

700
01:32:16,043 --> 01:32:18,709
..you might come...to like me.

701
01:33:23,418 --> 01:33:26,084
Stop complaining, I said!

702
01:33:26,126 --> 01:33:27,709
And be quiet.

703
01:33:27,751 --> 01:33:29,209
You'll just have to be naked

704
01:33:29,251 --> 01:33:32,626
until I've finished washing
and drying your clothes.

705
01:33:34,043 --> 01:33:36,834
I don't mind if you're cold.
Be quiet.

706
01:33:50,501 --> 01:33:53,668
No, we're not supposed to
visit him.

707
01:34:06,918 --> 01:34:08,418
What?

708
01:34:16,043 --> 01:34:17,543
You're bad!

709
01:34:32,751 --> 01:34:35,626
♪ The grand old Duke of York

710
01:34:35,668 --> 01:34:37,834
♪ He had 10,000 men

711
01:34:37,876 --> 01:34:40,543
♪ He marched them up
to the top of the hill

712
01:34:40,584 --> 01:34:42,876
♪ And he marched them
down again

713
01:34:42,918 --> 01:34:45,251
♪ And when they were up,
they were up

714
01:34:45,293 --> 01:34:47,584
♪ And when they were down,
they were down

715
01:34:47,626 --> 01:34:50,251
♪ And when they were
only halfway up

716
01:34:50,293 --> 01:34:52,584
♪ They were neither up nor down

717
01:34:52,626 --> 01:34:55,293
♪ The grand old
Duke of York... ♪

718
01:34:57,501 --> 01:34:58,918
♪ He marched them up... ♪

719
01:34:58,959 --> 01:35:00,376
Crooked, Mr Stewart.

720
01:35:00,418 --> 01:35:02,584
♪ And he marched them
down again. ♪

721
01:35:02,626 --> 01:35:03,834
Crooked.

722
01:35:08,918 --> 01:35:12,168
Mother wanted me
to give this to Mr Baines.

723
01:35:12,209 --> 01:35:15,459
I thought maybe it was not
the proper thing to do.

724
01:35:16,793 --> 01:35:18,293
Shall I open it?

725
01:35:18,334 --> 01:35:20,001
No. Give it to me.

726
01:36:29,334 --> 01:36:31,043
Why?

727
01:36:31,084 --> 01:36:32,584
I trusted you!

728
01:36:35,918 --> 01:36:38,168
I trusted you! I trusted you!

729
01:36:38,209 --> 01:36:40,001
Do you hear?!

730
01:36:40,043 --> 01:36:43,168
Why do you make me do it?
Why do you make me hurt you?

731
01:36:45,334 --> 01:36:47,043
We could be happy!

732
01:36:48,834 --> 01:36:50,959
You have
made me angry! Speak!

733
01:36:57,876 --> 01:36:59,751
You lied to me!

734
01:36:59,793 --> 01:37:01,501
You will answer for this!

735
01:37:01,543 --> 01:37:04,043
Speak or not,
you will answer for this!

736
01:37:28,793 --> 01:37:30,501
Do you love him?!

737
01:37:30,543 --> 01:37:32,293
Do you?!

738
01:37:34,459 --> 01:37:38,293
Is it him you love?
She says <i>noooo!</i>

739
01:37:40,918 --> 01:37:43,334
<i>Mother!</i>

740
01:37:44,834 --> 01:37:46,334
Mother!

741
01:38:45,543 --> 01:38:47,043
Mumma!

742
01:38:52,334 --> 01:38:53,918
You give this to Baines.

743
01:38:55,168 --> 01:38:57,376
Tell him, if he ever tries
to see her again,

744
01:38:57,418 --> 01:38:58,709
I'll take off another

745
01:38:58,751 --> 01:39:00,959
and another and another.

746
01:39:06,834 --> 01:39:08,626
Mother!
Run!

747
01:39:27,918 --> 01:39:30,001
What has happened?

748
01:39:30,043 --> 01:39:32,876
Hush, hush.

749
01:39:36,001 --> 01:39:37,501
What is it?

750
01:39:40,293 --> 01:39:42,959
You're not to see her
or he'll chop her up!

751
01:39:47,001 --> 01:39:49,001
What happened?

752
01:39:49,043 --> 01:39:50,793
Tell me.

753
01:39:50,834 --> 01:39:52,709
Tell me!

754
01:39:58,501 --> 01:40:00,168
Where is she?

755
01:40:00,209 --> 01:40:02,251
Shh. Quiet down!

756
01:40:02,293 --> 01:40:04,376
Quiet down. Where is she?

757
01:40:04,418 --> 01:40:07,459
He chopped it off!

758
01:40:07,501 --> 01:40:11,376
What did she tell him?

759
01:40:21,501 --> 01:40:23,959
I'm going to crush his skull.

760
01:40:24,001 --> 01:40:25,501
<i>Nooo!</i>

761
01:40:25,543 --> 01:40:27,751
No, no!

762
01:40:27,793 --> 01:40:30,959
He'll chop her up!

763
01:40:50,251 --> 01:40:52,001
You pushed me too hard.

764
01:40:52,043 --> 01:40:54,543
You cannot send love to him.
You cannot do that.

765
01:40:54,584 --> 01:40:56,584
Just...even...

766
01:40:56,626 --> 01:40:59,626
..even to think about it
makes me very angry.

767
01:41:04,834 --> 01:41:06,501
I meant to love you.

768
01:41:08,834 --> 01:41:10,543
I clipped your wing,
that's all.

769
01:41:13,001 --> 01:41:17,334
♪ We will be together

770
01:41:17,376 --> 01:41:21,376
♪ You will see,
it will be better... ♪

771
01:41:23,418 --> 01:41:25,709
Are you hot?

772
01:41:25,751 --> 01:41:27,251
Oh, my sweet lovebird.

773
01:42:41,001 --> 01:42:42,751
Are you feeling better?

774
01:43:01,376 --> 01:43:02,876
What?

775
01:44:19,043 --> 01:44:20,543
I look at you...

776
01:44:21,709 --> 01:44:23,209
..at your face.

777
01:44:24,626 --> 01:44:28,293
I've had that face
in my head, hating it,

778
01:44:28,334 --> 01:44:30,626
but now I'm here seeing it...

779
01:44:33,001 --> 01:44:34,501
..there's nothing.

780
01:44:36,293 --> 01:44:38,001
You have your marks.

781
01:44:38,043 --> 01:44:40,918
You look at me through
your eyes. Yes.

782
01:44:42,959 --> 01:44:44,543
You're even afraid of me.

783
01:44:47,084 --> 01:44:48,584
Get up.

784
01:44:56,876 --> 01:44:58,376
Baines...

785
01:45:00,918 --> 01:45:02,668
..has Ada ever spoken to you?

786
01:45:05,418 --> 01:45:07,209
You mean in signs?

787
01:45:09,334 --> 01:45:10,834
No, words.

788
01:45:12,918 --> 01:45:15,251
Have you ever heard words?

789
01:45:15,293 --> 01:45:18,168
No, not words.

790
01:45:18,209 --> 01:45:20,584
You never thought
you heard words?

791
01:45:26,168 --> 01:45:27,834
I heard it here.

792
01:45:27,876 --> 01:45:31,709
I heard a voice...
there in my head.

793
01:45:34,251 --> 01:45:36,793
I watched her lips. They
didn't make the words, but...

794
01:45:38,209 --> 01:45:42,001
..yet the harder I listened...

795
01:45:42,043 --> 01:45:43,959
..the clearer I heard her.

796
01:45:44,001 --> 01:45:47,043
You punished her wrongly.
It was me, my fault.

797
01:45:51,584 --> 01:45:53,084
She said...

798
01:45:57,501 --> 01:45:59,584
.."I am afraid of my will...

799
01:46:01,209 --> 01:46:04,168
"..of what it might do,
it is so strange and strong."

800
01:46:05,793 --> 01:46:07,334
She said...

801
01:46:09,626 --> 01:46:11,709
.."I have to go. Let me go.

802
01:46:13,168 --> 01:46:15,834
"Let Baines take me away.

803
01:46:15,876 --> 01:46:17,709
"Let him try and save me."

804
01:46:20,793 --> 01:46:22,918
I wish her gone.

805
01:46:22,959 --> 01:46:24,793
I wish... <i>you gone.</i>

806
01:46:28,876 --> 01:46:30,668
I want to wake up and...

807
01:46:32,793 --> 01:46:36,293
..and find that this...
was all a dream.

808
01:46:36,334 --> 01:46:37,834
That's what I want.

809
01:46:54,793 --> 01:46:56,376
It's a terrible shock.

810
01:46:56,418 --> 01:46:58,084
Aye, it is.

811
01:46:58,126 --> 01:46:59,709
Poor dear.

812
01:48:29,834 --> 01:48:31,293
No. She needs it.
She must have it.

813
01:49:51,001 --> 01:49:53,043
What did she say?

814
01:49:53,084 --> 01:49:55,959
She said,
"Throw the piano overboard."

815
01:49:56,001 --> 01:49:59,209
It's quite safe.
They are managing it.

816
01:50:01,209 --> 01:50:04,626
She doesn't want it.
She says it's spoiled.

817
01:50:05,918 --> 01:50:08,876
I've been given the key.
I'll have it mended.

818
01:50:10,501 --> 01:50:11,918
Baines.

819
01:50:19,126 --> 01:50:20,751
Please, Ada.

820
01:50:20,793 --> 01:50:22,293
Ple... Ada!

821
01:50:23,459 --> 01:50:26,334
You will regret it. It's your
piano. I want you to have it.

822
01:50:26,376 --> 01:50:28,001
She doesn't want it!
Ada, sit down.

823
01:50:28,043 --> 01:50:29,626
Sit... Sit down!

824
01:50:32,376 --> 01:50:34,334
Throw it over!
Sit down.

825
01:50:34,376 --> 01:50:37,084
Alright, we'll throw it over.

826
01:52:56,251 --> 01:52:57,876
<i>What a death.</i>

827
01:53:03,834 --> 01:53:05,418
<i>What a chance.</i>

828
01:53:10,376 --> 01:53:12,001
<i>What a surprise.</i>

829
01:53:20,459 --> 01:53:22,834
<i>My will has chosen life.</i>

830
01:53:34,876 --> 01:53:39,584
<i>Still, it has had me spooked,
and many others besides.</i>

831
01:53:42,751 --> 01:53:44,959
<i>I teach piano now in Nelson.</i>

832
01:53:48,001 --> 01:53:50,459
<i>George has fashioned me
a metal fingertip.</i>

833
01:53:51,751 --> 01:53:54,501
<i>I'm quite the town freak,
which satisfies.</i>

834
01:54:17,251 --> 01:54:18,793
Bah, bah, bah...

835
01:54:18,834 --> 01:54:20,959
<i>I am learning to speak.</i>

836
01:54:21,001 --> 01:54:23,918
<i>My sound is still so bad,
I feel ashamed.</i>

837
01:54:23,959 --> 01:54:25,543
Deh, deh...

838
01:54:25,584 --> 01:54:29,334
<i>I practise only when I am alone
and it is dark.</i>

839
01:54:29,376 --> 01:54:34,084
Hah, hah. Kah, kah, kah.

840
01:54:34,126 --> 01:54:38,168
Vah, vah, vah.

841
01:54:38,209 --> 01:54:42,293
Bah, bah, bah.

842
01:54:42,334 --> 01:54:44,876
Pah, pah...

843
01:54:48,459 --> 01:54:50,043
Hmm.

844
01:55:22,376 --> 01:55:26,501
<i>At night, I think of my piano
in its ocean grave.</i>

845
01:55:30,543 --> 01:55:34,501
<i>And sometimes of myself
floating above it.</i>

846
01:55:36,918 --> 01:55:40,334
<i>Down there, everything is
so still and silent</i>

847
01:55:40,376 --> 01:55:43,168
<i>that it lulls me to sleep.</i>

848
01:55:43,209 --> 01:55:45,959
<i>It is a weird lullaby.</i>

849
01:55:46,001 --> 01:55:49,293
<i>And so it is - it is mine.</i>

850
01:55:51,209 --> 01:55:56,001
<i>There is a silence
where hath been no sound.</i>

851
01:55:56,043 --> 01:56:00,751
<i>There is a silence where
no sound may be,</i>

852
01:56:00,793 --> 01:56:03,043
<i>In the cold grave -</i>

853
01:56:03,084 --> 01:56:05,668
<i>Under the deep, deep sea.</i>

